1. Data description

Data were taken from these websites:
http://www.pcn.minambiente.it/mattm/catalogo-metadati/, accessed on 12 January 2020;
https://soilgrids.org, accessed on 16 January 2020; http://www.sinanet.isprambiente.it/it/sia-ispra, accessed on 28 January 2020.

This dataset contains the data from satellites observation of forests in Italy. It contains 7726 observations and 25 variables, and I will use 22 of them, I will remove the ID (fid), the LONGITUDE and the LATITUDE (but I will keep the original dataset because they are useful to visualize the data). The goal of this project is to predict the variables DLT, a binary variable with values of 1 for broad-leaves forests and values of 2 for needle-leaves forests. All the other variables are numeric variables. The variable BioClimReg can be considered both as numeric or as a factor, because it represents the different bio-climatic regions, taking values from 1 to 5. But since there are values (around 3000) that are not integers, meaning that a forest can be in between two climatic regions, I decided to keep this variable as a numeric one. Another possible way to deal with this variables is to round the non-integers values to the nearest integer.

There is a full description of the variables in the dataset. (Units inside parenteses, if no units present, the variable is dimensionless).
- fid: index.
- DLT: response variable having values 0 for broad-leaves forests and 1 for needle-leaves forests.
- LONGITUDE: longitude.
- LATITUDE: latidute.
- dCoastLog: Distance from shoreline (Log10). (km)
- Lat: Latitude 20 m cellcentroid. (Degrees)
- CRFann: Annual Cumulated Rainfall. (mm/year)
- BioClimReg: different bio-climatic regions.
- Elev: Elevation.
- PHIHOX: pH index measured in water solution. (pH)
- LAI_delta: Annual delta LAI Winter (December, January, February). (\({m^{2}}/{m^{2}}\))
- LAI_std: Annual standard deviation LAI. (\({m^{2}}/{m^{2}}\))
- BDTICM: Absolute depth to bedrock. (cm)
- LAI_djf_avg: Winter (December, January, February) average LAI. (\({m^{2}}/{m^{2}}\))
- TannNorm: Normalized annual average air temperature. (Celsius)

Sentinel (satellite) data.

  • B8A_m07: Sentinel-2 MSI B8A value at yearly month 07.
  • B11_m03: Sentinel-2 MSI B11 value at yearly month 03.
  • B11_m05: Sentinel-2 MSI B11 value at yearly month 05.
  • B11_m07: Sentinel-2 MSI B11 value at yearly month 07.
  • B11_m08: Sentinel-2 MSI B11 value at yearly month 08.
  • B12_m03: Sentinel-2 MSI B12 value at yearly month 03.
  • EVI_m03: Sentinel-2 MSI EVI value at yearly month 03.
  • RI_m03: Sentinel-2 MSI RI value at yearly month 03.
  • CRI1_m10: Sentinel-2 MSI CRI1 value at yearly month 10.
  • NDYI_m10: Sentinel-2 MSI NDYI value at yearly month 10.

In this project I will use some supervised classification methods to predict the variable DLT, such as classification trees, random forest and support vector machine.

I did the analysis with R, using the following libraries:
- (readr): load data.
- (dplyr): data manipulation.
- (knitr): captions.
- (MASS): forward and backward selection.
- (caret): classification training (cross validation).
- (pROC): accuracy measure.
- (glmnet): Lasso.
- (tree): classification trees. - (maptree): tree plots
- (randomForest): random forest.
- (e1071): SVM.

2. Data manipulation

First of all, I removed the observations containing NAs, so now the dataset contains 7010 observation, then I transformed the DLT from a numeric to a factor with two classes, 0 for broad-leaves forests and 1 for needle-leaves forests.
Looking at the distribution of the the two classes, I noticed that the broad-leaves forests are many more than the others, hence I decided to do an oversampling, just on the training set, to have the same number of observation for the two classes.
The next step was to split the dataset into training and test, with the training being 80% of the observations. Then, I removed from the dataset the variables that I did not need for my analysis: the ID, the longitude and the latitude.

Table 1: DLT distribution
class freq
broad-leaves 5512
needle-leaves 1498

Using oversampling for the training set, I will have a balanced dataset.

Table 2: DLT distribution on the training set (after oversampling)
class freq
broad-leaves 4397
needle-leaves 4397

3. Data Analysis - Subset Selection

In this section I performed forward and backward selection, and also Lasso, on the full dataset in order to reduce the number of variables that I need to take into account to perform analysis.

3.1. Forward Selection

Performing forward selection, here it shows the fifteen regressors that I should consider in a further analysis.

##  [1] "B8A_m07"     "B11_m08"     "PHIHOX"      "LAI_djf_avg" "BioClimReg"

## [11] "B11_m07"     "B11_m05"     "TannNorm"    "EVI_m03"     "CRFann"

I then calculated the accuracy on the test set of this model, that is 90.54 %, and the accuracy of the same model, but using the best threshold according to the roc curve (0.53), that is 90.94 %, instead of the standard threshold (0.5).

Hence, for the following analysis, I will use the 7-regressors model chosen by Lasso.

4. Data Analysis - Classification Methods

In this section I checked which method predicted the classes better among classification trees, random forest and support vector machines.
For every method, I fitted a model using the training set found at the beginning of the paper, and predicted the data using the test set.

4.1. Classification tree

We fit a tree using the 7-regressor model found previously using Lasso.

We can see that the training error rate is 0.010 % (misclassification error rate)

From Table 7, the trees with the least number of CV errors is he 8-node tree, but there is not so much difference between the 8-node, 7-node and 2-node tree, thus, for a better visualization, I decided to plot the 7-node tree.

Fig. 3: 3-node Pruned Tree

From fig.3 we can see that the most important regressors are B8A_m07 and B11_m08. In particular, we can say that when B8A_m07 is less than 0.292 and B11_m08 is less than 0.12, DLT will be assigned to class 1 (needle-leaves). When B8A_m07 is higher than 0.292 AND B11_m08 is higher than 0.133, DLT will be assigned to class 0 (broad-leaves).

I then decided to apply both bagging and random forest, remembering that bagging is just a special case of a random forest with m = p

## accuracy: 93.51 %

Bagging has an accuracy of 93.51 %. It works better than the classification tree.

I then applied Random Forest (by default, for classifcation \(m =\sqrt{p}\), so in this case, since p is 7, m is rounded to 2).

4.4 Support Vector Machine

As last analysis, I decided that I wanted to fit a support vector machine model. I fitted three different models, one using a linear kernel, one a radial kernel and one with a polynomial kernel. I did this to see which kernel performs better.

I set for every model the cost = 10, for the radial kernel model, the parameter gamma = 0.5 and for the polynomial kernel model, the parameter d = 5. Before selecting this values, I tried different combinations and I selected the best ones in terms of accuracy. I did not perform CV because for SVM it is computationally very expensive.

## 
## accuracy linear: 89.59 %
## 
## accuracy radial: 92.44 %
## 
## accuracy polynomial: 92.08 %

The SVM model with radial kernel is the one with best accuracy, however, the accuracy on the polynomial model is similar.

5. Conclusion

Given the results I obtained from my analysis I can say that the two models that predicts the best the DLT is the Random Forest, with an accuracy of 94.44 %

I first decided the number of regressors to use using forward selection, backward selection and LASSO. The forward selection model recommended to use 15 regressors, with an accuracy of 90.51 % (92.57 % after CV). The backward selection recommended to use 17 regressors, with an accuracy of 90.09 % (92.71 % after CV).
The LASSO did choose 7 regressors with an accuracy of 89.59 % (I did not do CV on LASSO).
Since the accuracy of Lasso is similar to the accuracy of the other two methods, but Lasso did choose less regressors than the others, I decided to use the regressors found thanks to Lasso. I then fitted a Classification tree model, that gave me an accuracy of 91.51 %. Then, I tried bagging and random forests model, with accuracy respectively of 93.51 % and 94.44 %.
Lastly, I performed SVM, but the accuracy was not high as random forest. (92.44 % using radial kernel, it was less using linear or polynomial).

The support vector machine model and the classification tree perform quite good, having accuracy respectively of 92 % and 91 % circa. I expected the classification tree to perform worse compared to the random forest because a random forest is a combination of trees, so generally it performs better. The only reasons why sometimes decision trees are preferred is because of the interpretability. Thus with similar accuracy, in this case the random forest is better because it has an accuracy of 3 % higher, but with similar accuracy I would have chosen the classification tree as best model.

# FORWARD SELECTION ----

set.seed(1)
logistic_model <- glm(DLT ~ ., data = df_train, family = "binomial")
null_model <- glm(DLT ~ 1, data = df_train, family = "binomial")


regfit.fwd <- stepAIC(null_model,direction="forward",scope=list(upper=logistic_model,lower=null_model), trace = F)
names(coef(regfit.fwd))[-1] #15 regressors
set.seed(1)
pred <- predict(regfit.fwd, df_test, type = "response")
pred_class <- ifelse(pred <= 0.5, "broad-leaves", "needle-leaves")
pred_table <- table(df_test$DLT, pred_class)

pred_table %>%
  kable(caption ="**Table 3: prediction table forward model**")

accuracy <- (pred_table[1,1] + pred_table[2,2]) / nrow(df_test)
cat("accuracy:",round(accuracy*100, 2), "%") 

# increase accuracy

set.seed(1)
coords(roc(df_test$DLT, pred), "best", ret = c("threshold"))

  kable(caption ="**Table 4: prediction table forward model (threshold 0.53)**")

  kable(caption ="**Table 7: pruned tree values**")

# prune.misclass() function in order to prune the tree to obtain the tree-node tree.

accuracy <- (rf.table[1,1] + rf.table[2,2]) / nrow(df_test)
cat("accuracy:",round(accuracy*100, 2), "%") 
set.seed(1)

df_svm <- df %>%
  dplyr::select(DLT, BioClimReg, Elev, PHIHOX, B11_m08, LAI_djf_avg, LAI_delta, B8A_m07)

df_svm_train <- df_train %>%
  dplyr::select(DLT, BioClimReg, Elev, PHIHOX, B11_m08, LAI_djf_avg, LAI_delta, B8A_m07)

df_svm_test <- df_test %>%
  dplyr::select(DLT, BioClimReg, Elev, PHIHOX, B11_m08, LAI_djf_avg, LAI_delta, B8A_m07)

set.seed(1)
svm.fit <- svm(DLT ~ ., data = df_svm_train, kernel = "linear", cost = 10)
set.seed(1)
svm.fit2 <- svm(DLT ~ ., data = df_svm_train, kernel = "radial", cost = 10, gamma = 0.5)
set.seed(1)
svm.fit3 <- svm(DLT ~ ., data = df_svm_train, kernel = "polynomial", cost = 10, d = 5)

# check the performance on test set

pred.te <- predict(svm.fit, newdata = df_svm_test)
svm.table <- table(pred.te, df_svm_test$DLT)
accuracy <- (svm.table[1,1] + svm.table[2,2]) / nrow(df_svm_test)
cat("
accuracy linear:", round(mean(accuracy)*100,2), "%") 

pred.te <- predict(svm.fit2, newdata = df_svm_test)
svm.table <- table(pred.te, df_svm_test$DLT)
accuracy <- (svm.table[1,1] + svm.table[2,2]) / nrow(df_svm_test)
cat("
accuracy radial:", round(mean(accuracy)*100,2), "%") 

pred.te <- predict(svm.fit3, newdata = df_svm_test)
svm.table <- table(pred.te, df_svm_test$DLT)
accuracy <- (svm.table[1,1] + svm.table[2,2]) / nrow(df_svm_test)
cat("
accuracy polynomial:", round(mean(accuracy)*100,2), "%")
